arassment, reproductive freedom, incest, depression and addiction, or romantic relationships—and articulates a feminist approach to engaging with the problem or concern. Contributors include African American scholars, artists, activists, and business professionals who offer personal accunts of how they encountered feminist ideas and are using them now as a guide to living. The essays included reveal how feminist principles affect people's perceptions of their ability to change themselves and society, because the personal is not always self-evidently political.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAfrican American feministsxHistory. 0aFeminismzUnited StatesxHistory. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Feminist. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh1 a(Dee)Frisque, Deloise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAdams, Mary Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCleage, Pearl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDornell, Marian Cannon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDorothy, M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDotson, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreilla, Omar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGross, Carolyn E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson, Vanessa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLemons, Gary L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartin, Vera C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeal, Mark Anthony